-- Demo ledger seed — one-time bootstrap of the July 10–12 2026 prototype decision history.
--
-- WHY: this data was accumulated in the prototype's Postgres store while the demo was built. When the
-- ledger store moved to file-backed H2 (locked decision D8's primary option — "H2 file-backed"), the
-- 88 real decisions + their explanation/override overlays were ported here so a fresh `docker compose
-- up` comes up with a populated, demo-ready ledger (the Ledger Copilot's "45 of 88" story, the
-- compliance dashboard, and the customer portal all need history to be interesting).
--
-- HOW IT STAYS HONEST: this is a *seed*, not a runtime writer — the decision_records table is still
-- append-only and its ONLY runtime writer is JpaDecisionLedger. Flyway's schema-history table means
-- this migration runs exactly once, on a fresh database; the persisted H2 file never re-seeds. Rows
-- are inserted parent-first (records → explanations → overrides) to satisfy the FK constraints, and
-- the certificate sequence is advanced past the seeded max so the next real submission is
-- SG-2026-000089 with no UNIQUE collision.
--
-- REGRESSION TO AVOID / SAFE EXTENSION: demo data lives in the versioned migration chain only because
-- the whole Phase-1 dataset is synthetic. Before any real deployment this file is deleted and the
-- chain re-based (Phase-2 note) — a real ledger must never be seeded with fabricated decisions.
--
-- GENERATED from the prototype Postgres store via quote_literal (standard-SQL string escaping; the
-- payloads contain no newlines/backslashes, so H2 in PostgreSQL mode ingests these verbatim). Do not
-- hand-edit — regenerate from source if the demo dataset changes.

-- decision_records (88) — parent rows; full immutable DecisionRecord JSON in `payload`.

-- decision_explanations (76) — async explanation overlays, keyed by record_id.

-- decision_overrides (5) — supervisor approve/reject reviews, keyed by record_id.

-- Advance the certificate sequence past the seeded max (88) so the next runtime allocation is 89.
ALTER SEQUENCE certificate_seq RESTART WITH 89;
